d J. Lautenbach, Long&#8208;term Lidar Observations of the Gravity Wave activity near the Mesopause at arecibo, atmos. Chem. Phys. Discuss., (DOI: 10.5194/acp&#8208;2018&#8208;731)\r\n \r\nReid, I.M., J. Lautenbach, a.D. MacKinnon, a. Klekociuk, L. Twigger and D.J. Ottaway, The Buckland Park Rayleigh Lidar: Description and Early Results, annual Meeting of the asia Oceania Geosciences Society (aOGS), aS30&#8208;D4&#8208;aM1&#8208;319a&#8208;003.\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2017</h6>\r\n\r\nPiccone, a. N. and J. Lautenbach, upgrading the arecibo Potassium Lidar Receiver for Meridional Wind Measurements, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa21a&#8208;2507\r\n \r\nFranco&#8208;Diaz, E., S. Raizada, C. G. Marques Brum and J. Lautenbach, Estimation of 557.7 nm Emission altitude using Co&#8208;located Lidars and Photometers over arecibo, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa21a&#8208;2503\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2016</h6>\r\n\r\nFranco&#8208;Diaz, E., J. Lautenbach, J.S. Friedman and S. Raizada, Enhanced Capabilities of the arecibo Observatory Resonance Lidar Systems, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa43B&#8208;2397\r\n  \r\nRaizada, S., J.S. Friedman, C. G. Marques Brum, J. Lautenbach and E. Franco, Comparison of mesospheric Na and K layers and tidal structures during the summer and winter over arecibo, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa21a&#8208;2353\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2015</h6>\r\n\r\nRaizada, S., C. G. Marques Brum, C.a. Tepley, J. Lautenbach, J.S. Friedman, J.D. Mathews, F.T. Djuth and C. Kerr, First simultaneous measurements of Na and K thermospheric layers along with TILs from arecibo, Geophysical Research Letters 42 (23), (DOI: 10.1002/2015GL066714)\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2012</h6>\r\n\r\nFriedman, J.S., D. Maldonado&#8208;Nieves, I.Gonzalez, J. Lautenbach, X. Chu, Ja. Smith and W. Huang, High spectral resolution test and calibration of an ultra&#8208;narrowband Faraday anomalous dispersion optical filter for use in daytime mesospheric resonance Doppler lidar, Journal of atmospheric and Solar&#8208;Terrestrial Physics 80 (DOI: 10.1016/j.jastp.2012.01.01)\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2010</h6>\r\n\r\nHoffner, J., J. Lautenbach and F.J. Lubken, Temperature, NLC/aerosol and metal observations by mobile potassium/iron Doppler lidar at Spitsbergen, 78&#730; N and andoya, 69&#730; N, 38th COSPaR Scientific assembly 38, 4\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2009</h6>\r\n\r\nLubken, J.F., J. Lautenbach, J. Hoffner, M. Rapp and M. Zecha, First continuous temperature measurements within polar mesosphere summer echoes, Journal of atmospheric and Solar&#8208;Terrestrial Physics 71 (3&#8208;4), 453&#8208;463\r\n \r\nHoffner, J. and J. Lautenbach, Daylight measurements of mesopause temperature and vertical wind with the mobile scanning iron lidar, Optics letters 34 (9), 1351&#8208;1353\r\n  \r\n<br><h6>2008</h6>\r\n\r\nGerding, M., J. Hoffner, J. Lautenbach, M. Rauthe and F.J. Lubken, Seasonal variation of nocturnal temperatures between 1 and 105 km altitude at 54&#730; N observed by lidar, atmospheric Chemistry and Physics 8 (24), 7465&#8208;7482\r\n    \r\nLuebken F.J., J. Hoeffner and J. Lautenbach, The Mobile Scanning Iron Lidar: a new approach for Background Free Doppler Measurements of Rayleigh/Mie/Resonance Scattering at Daylight, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa53D&#8208;04\r\n \r\nLuebken F.J., J. Lautenbach, M. Rapp, J. Hoeffner and M. Zecha, Temperatures and PMSE at Spitsbergen: implications for physical processes in the upper atmosphere, 37th COSPaR Scientific assembly 37, 1836\r\n  \r\n<br><h6>2006</h6>\r\n\r\nStrelnikov, B., M. Rapp, T.a. Blix, N. Engler, J. Hoffner, J. Lautenbach, F.J. Lubken, B. Smiley and M. Friedrich, In situ observations of small scale neutral and plasma dynamics in the mesosphere/lower thermosphere at 79 N, advances in Space Research 38 (11), 2388&#8208;2393\r\n \r\nHoffner, J., J. Lautenbach, C. Fricke&#8208;Begemann and F.J. Lubken, Polar mesosphere temperature observations by lidar and falling sphere at 78 N Proceedings of the 23rd ILRC Conference, Nara, Japan, 24&hyphen;28 July 2006, 373&#8208;376\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2004</h6>\r\n \r\nLubken, F.J, J. Hoffner, J. Lautenbach, a. Mullemann, M. Zecha and J. Rottger, Small scale layers and the thermal structure in the high latitude (78&#730; N) summer mesosphere, 35th COSPaR Scientific assembly 35, 2025\r\n \r\n<br><h6>2003</h6>\r\n \r\nHoffner, J., C. Fricke&#8208;Begemann, J. Lautenbach and P. Menzel, Seasonal Temperatures by Potassium Lidar at Spitsbergen, 78&#730; N, aGu Fall Meeting abstract id. Sa42a&#8208;07\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n ', 'https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jens_Lautenbach'),
(10, NULL, NULL, 'http://outreach.naic.edu/pkg/webutils/images/Anish.png', 'Anish Roshi', NULL, '315', 'anish.damodaran@ucf.edu', 'an564768@ucf.edu', 'Senior Scientist, \r\nHead Of Radio Astronomy', 'Astronomy', 'radar, ipa, galaxy, ', 'radar, ipa, galaxy, ', 'Galactic Interstellar Medium, Molecular Cloud Formation, Starformation, Radio Astronomy Instrumentation', 'Dr. Anish Roshi research focuses on the study of molecular cloud formation using low-frequency carbon recombination lines and radio frequency interference mitigation. He also studies Phased Array Feed theory, system design and signal processing.', 'Dr. Anish Roshi graduated with an engineering degree in electronics and communications from the University of Kerala. In 1989, he joined the Tata Institute of Fundamental Research (TIFR), National Center for Radio Astrophysics, Pune as a Research Associate/Scientific Oficer. At TIFR, he completed his Ph.D (Physics) specializing in Radio Astronomy (1999) and was appointed as a member of the faculty. \r\n\r\nHe was a Jansky postdoctoral fellow at the National Radio Astronomy Observatory (NRAO), USA between 2000 and 2002. On completion of the post doctoral fellowship, Dr Roshi joined the Raman Research Institute (RRI), Bangalore. While at RRI his biggest contribution was in leading a team of engineers in successfully designing and building a digital receiver for the Murchison Widefield Array, located at Western Australia. \r\n\r\nIn 2010, Dr. Roshi moved to the National Radio Astronomy Observatory (NRAO), USA. At NRAO, he was the System Architect and Project Scientist for the Versatile Astronomical Spectrometer that was built for the Green Bank Telescope (GBT). He was also the System Architect for the Phased Array Feed (PAF) project. PAFs are specialized feed to increase the field of view of radio telescope. At Arecibo Observatory, he is working with the team building the 40 beam PAF for the telescope.\r\n\r\nSince 2018, he is a Senior Observatory Scientist for Radio Astronomy at the Arecibo Observatory. Dr. Roshi has an active research interest in Astronomy. His primary focus has been the study of galactic Interstellar Medium (ISM), molecular cloud formation and massive star formation using radio recombination lines (RRLs). At Arecibo Observatory, he continues such studies using the sensitive telescope.', 'Dr. Anish Roshi projects include the study of molecular cloud formation using low-frequency carbon recombination lines, radio frequency interference excision technique to detect weak astronomical spectral lines, and applying focal field interferometry with the Arecibo telescope.', NULL, 'https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/search/p_=0&q=%20author%3A%22Anish%20Roshi%22&sort=date%20desc%2C%20bibcode%20desc', 'http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1732-5990/'),
(11, NULL, NULL, 'http://outreach.naic.edu/ao/sites/default/files/Pedrina.jpg', 'Pedrina Terra dos Santos', NULL, '258', 'pedrina.santos@ucf.edu', NULL, 'Senior Observatory Scientist', 'Space & Atmospheric Sciences', 'Space & Atmospheric Sciences', 'atmosphere', 'Atmospheric Physics,\r\nAeronomy,\r\nIonosphere-Thermosphere,\r\nMlt Region,\r\nAirglow Waves\r\n', 'Dr. Terras research focuses on the remote sensing studies of the Earth\'s atmosphere dynamics using Fabry-Perot interferometry, imagery, and photometry. Her main research topic is the coupling between the lower and higher atmosphere via waves-induced processes.', 'Dr. Terra has been leading the project of the Remote Optical Facility (ROF) at the island of Culebra (150 km east of AO) since 2015, which was established to complement the optical observational capability of AO. Nowadays the ROF is populated with optical and radar receivers\'  instruments obtained from several peers reviewed proposals.Dr. Terra is from Brazil and has a bachelor\'s degree in Electrical Engineer. During her second year at the university, she started a fellowship at the National Institute for Space Research (INPE). There she heard about Arecibo Observatory (AO) for the first time and fell in love with space sciences. When she graduated, she started her masters at INPE in the area of Space Geophysics, under the supervision of a former AO\' s scientist to study the features of the plasma bubbles over the Brazilian territory. a couple of years later, she started her Ph. D. at INPE to study the dynamics of the ionosphere&#8208;thermosphere system and had the opportunity to spend part of her Ph. D. at the university of Sheffield, England. \r\n Dr. Terra started at Arecibo Observatory in 2016 as a postdoctoral fellow at Space and atmospheric Science group. Since then, she dedicates her time to optical sciences and provides her expertise and experience of the remote sensing of the mesosphere and thermosphere of the Earth, airglow emissions, and gravity waves.', 'Dr. Terra has been leading the project of the Remote Optical Facility (ROF) at the island of Culebra (150 km east of AO) since 2015, which was established to complement the optical observational capability of AO. Nowadays the ROF is populated with optical and radar receivers\'  instruments obtained from several peers reviewed proposals.', '', '', 'https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9768-4597');
INSERT INTO `science_staff_3` (`ID`, `Hora_de_inicio`, `Hora_de_finalización`, `IMAGE`, `FULL_NAME`, `FIRST_NAME`, `PHONE_EXT`, `PRIMARY_EMAIL`, `UCF_EMAIL`, `POSITION`, `DEPARTMENT`, `CATEGORIES`, `KEYWORDS`, `RESEARCH_AREAS`, `RESEARCH_DESCRIPTION`, `BIOGRAPHY`, `PROJECTS`, `MENTORING`, `PUBLICATIONS`, `ORCID_LINK`) VALUES
(12, NULL, NULL, 'http://www.naic.edu/ao/sites/default/files/Flavianne%20%281%29.jpg', 'Flaviane Venditti', NULL, '603', 'venditti@ucf.edu', NULL, 'Observatory Scientist', 'Planetary Sciences', 'Planetary Sciences', 'radar, asteroids', 'Radar Observations, Orbital Dynamics, Asteroid Modeling, Asteroid Deflection Techniques, Orbital Debris', 'Dr. Venditti is part of the planetary radar science group working primarily with radar observations of near-Earth objects (NEOs) and characterization to support planetary defense. Regarding radar observations, she has a special interest in astrometry and asteroid shape modeling. In addition, she has a background in orbital dynamics, also working with orbit perturbation and asteroid impact mitigation strategies.', 'Dr. Venditti started her scientific career as a Bachelor in Physics/Astronomy at the University of Sao Paulo, where she was part of the Polarimetry group working with observations at the National Laboratory for Astrophysics (LNA) in Minas Gerais, Brazil. Besides observations, she was also interested in celestial mechanics and space missions, which led her to pursue a Master\'s (2009) and Ph.D (2013) degree in Space Engineering at the National Institute for Space Research, Brazil, focused on Astrodynamics. \r\nDuring her Ph.D, she worked with orbital maneuvers around irregularly shaped bodies, developing a method to model the gravitational field of asteroids with low computational effort using Arecibo\'s planetary radar data. She was a postdoctoral scientist for one year at the same institution, working with orbit perturbation, and in Montreal for 2.5 years working with dynamics of asteroid deflection at McGill University, Canada. She joined the Arecibo staff in May 2017.', 'Dr. Venditti current grant project was provided by NASA Grant #80NSSC19K0523, which was awarded to the University of Central Florida (UCF) for 2019-2024. She is a team member of  NASA\'s DART mission investigation team (https://dart.jhuapl.edu/) and the CLASS Planetary Landing Team (https://sciences.ucf.edu/class/landing-team/).\r\nOther projects Dr. Venditti is include study of dynamics of asteroid deflection using tethers, asteroid shape modeling, orbit perturbation around small bodies, as well as space debris radar detection and characterization.\r\n\r\n', '', '<h5>Peer-reviewed first-author publications</h5>\r\n\r\nVenditti, F. C. F., Marchi, L. O., Misra, a. K. D. O., Prado, F. B. a. \'Dynamics of tethered asteroid systems to support planetary defense\' . European Physical Journal Special Topics (EPJ ST). (Special issue: Celestial Mechanics in the XXIst century), 2020. (In Press)\r\n\r\nVenditti, F. C. F.; Prado, A. F. B. A.; \'Mapping Orbits regarding Perturbations due to the Gravitational Field of a Cube\' . Mathematical Problems in Engineering, v. 2015, p. 1-11, 2015.\r\n  \r\nVenditti, F. C. F.; Prado, A. F. B. A.; \'A Method to Evaluate the Perturbation of Non-spherical Bodies\' . Advances in the Astronautical Sciences, v. 153, p. 1143-1163, 2015.\r\n\r\nVenditti, F. C. F.; Rocco, E. M. \'Modelling asteroids to assist in orbiting and landing missions\' . Advances in the Astronautical Sciences, Volume 162, AAS 17-768, 2018.\r\n  \r\nVenditti, F. C. F.; Rocco, E. M.; Prado, A. F. B. A. \'Trajectory control around non-spherical bodies modeled with the formulation for parallelepipeds\' . Journal of Physics: Conference Series, Vol. 465, No. 1, p. 012008, IOP Publishing, 2013.\r\n \r\nVenditti F. C. F., Rocco E. M., Prado A. F. B. A. \'Orbital trajectories control around non-spherical bodies\' . American Institute of Physics Proceedings, Vol. 1493, p. 1083, 2012.\r\n \r\nVenditti, F. C. F.; Rocco, E. M. ; Prado, A. F. B. A.; Suhkanov, A. \'Gravity-assisted maneuvers applied in the multi-objective optimization of interplanetary trajectories\' . Acta Astronautica, v. 67, n. 9, p. 1255-1271, 2010.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h5>Co-authored peer-reviewed publications</h5>\r\n\r\nA.K. Virkki, S.E. Marshall, F. C. F. Venditti, L.F. Zambrano Marin, E.G. Rivera-Valentin, P.a. Taylor. \'2016 aZ_8\' , Central Bureau Electronic Telegrams, 2019.\r\n\r\nMagalhaes, A. M., Pereyra, A., Melgarejo, R., de Matos, L., Carciofi, A. C., Venditti, F. C. F., Valentim, R. and Gabriel, V. S. The Southern Optical/Infrared Survey of Interstellar Polarization in the Galaxy. In AIP Conference Proceedings (Vol. 784, No. 1, pp. 715-720). American Institute of Physics, 2005.\r\n  \r\nMagalhaes, A. M., Pereyra, A., Melgarejo, R., de Matos, L., Carciofi, a. C., Venditti, F. C. F., Valentim, R., Vidotto, A. A., da Silva, F. N., de Souza, P. P. F. and Faria, H., 2005, December. A Southern optical/infrared survey of Interstellar Polarization. In Astronomical Polarimetry: Current Status and Future Directions (Vol. 343, p. 305), 2005.\r\n   \r\nTaylor, P. A., Rivera-Valentin, E. G., Benner, L. a., Marshall, S. E., Virkki, a. K., Venditti, F. C. F., Zambrano-Marin, L. F., Bhiravarasu, S. S., Aponte-Hernandez, B., Sanchez-Vahamonde, C.R. and Giorgini, J. D. Arecibo radar observations of near-Earth asteroid (3200) Phaethon during the 2017 apparition. Planetary and Space Science, 167, pp.1-8, 2019.\r\n', 'https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9150-8376'),
(13, NULL, NULL, 'http://outreach.naic.edu/pkg/webutils/images/PK.JPG', 'Periasamy K. Manoharan', 'Periasamy', '617', 'Periasamy.Manoharan@ucf.edu', 'Periasamy.Manoharan@ucf.edu', 'Senior Observatory Scientist', 'Astronomy', 'astronomy, galaxy, radar, ', 'Galaxy', 'Multi-Wavelength Studies Of Eruptive Sun,\r\nPhysical Properties Of Solar Wind,\r\nSpace Weather Events, \r\nTurbulence,\r\nPulsars,\r\nRadio Astronomy Techniques', 'Manoharan developed a unique method to determine the speed and other physical properties of the solar wind using interplanetary scintillation (IPS) measurements from a single radio telescope. His studies have led to important results pertaining to solar wind and Space Weather processes/effects in the inner heliosphere. Manoharan explained for the first time the formation of the twisted magnetic loop system (which was later named sigmoid ) at sites of coronal mass ejections (CMEs). Studies by him and his co-researchers have been useful to understand fundamental issues regarding the physics of magnetic reconnection on the sun and associated release of large energy. He has guided a number of students on studies of sun, space weather, pulsar, radio astronomical system development, etc.', 'Dr P.K. Manoharan joined Tata Institute of Fundamental Research (TIFR) in 1975, immediately after his BSc (Special Physics) at American College, Madurai and since then he was associated with the Ooty Radio Telescope. He completed his doctoral studies in 1991 at TIFR, and then spent one year (1993) as a JSPS Fellow at the Solar-Terrestrial Environment Laboratory, Japan, for a year and half (1995-96) as a Visiting Fellow at the Observatoire de Paris, Meudon, France, and nearly two years (2002-03) as a Visiting Scientist at the Goddard Space Flight Center, NASA and University of Maryland, USA. He was an academic faculty member of TIFR and served as the Professor and Director of Ooty Radio Observatory, Radio Astronomy Centre (2004-2018). Manoharan was a member (2009-2014) and served as the Vice-President of IAU Commission 49 (Interplanetary Plasma and Heliosphere) (2014-2016). He was the Secretary (2005-2009) and the President (2010-2012) of Asia-Oceania Geosciences Society (aOGS), Solar-Terrestrial Science Section. He served in the Editorial Board of `Geoscience Letters for four years. He currently serves in Editorial Boards ofJournal of Space Weather and Space Climate and Indian Journal of Radio & Space Physics.\r\n \r\nStarting from October 2019, Dr. Manoharan is a Senior Observatory Scientist at the Arecibo Observatory. He has initiated heliophysics and space weather studies with the Arecibo Telescope.', 'Dr. Manoharan performs space weather studies with the Arecibo Telescope. He does research in solar wind acceleration, observations of solar coronal jets, plasma tail turbulence of Comet ATLAS, and in probing the plasma tail of Interstellar Comet 2I/Borisov', NULL, 'Manoharan PUBLICATIONS (NASA Astrophysics Data System (ADS) Link)\r\n \r\nhttps://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/search/filter_database_fq_database=OR&filter_database_fq_database=database%3a%22astronomy%22&fq=%7B!type%3Daqp%20v%3D%24fq_database%7D&fq_database=(database%3a%22astronomy%22)&q=author%3a%22Manoharan%2C%20P%20K%22&sort=date%20desc%2C%20bibcode%20desc&p_=0', 'https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4274-211X'),
(14, NULL, NULL, 'http://outreach.naic.edu/ao/sites/default/files/Luisa-Fernanda-Zambrano.jpg', 'Luisa Fernanda Zambrano-Marin', NULL, '606', 'luisa.zambranomarin@ucf.edu', NULL, 'Science Operations Associate', 'Planetary Sciences', 'planets, other', 'planets, other', 'Asteroids, Planetary Science, Space Exploration, Light Scattering', 'Zambrano-Marin studies relationships between polarization properties and near surface bulk density along with known relationships between polarization and spectral class of near-Earth Objects observed with radar. She processes recent data sets and extract measurements for scientific analysis and publication. In addition, Zambrano-Marin studies radar scattering effects on: circular polarization ratios, radar albedo, and dispersion of signal, refractive indices, electric permittivity and its geometry implications on body composition while also applying Earth analogs of radar measurements to refine our understanding of planetary surfaces and extract relationships on objects evolution and physical parameters.', 'Luisa Fernanda was born in Colombia, she moved to Puerto Rico in 1998. She did her undergraduate degree in applied Physics at Metropolitan University (UMET, Ana G. Mendez University System). As an undergraduate, she did research with the Vatican Observatory Group in Castel-Gandolfo for the Kepler Mission. She competed her Masters in Space Studies at the International Space University (ISU, Strasbourg, France) and has been an active member of the Space community ever since. Her Msc. Thesis was done at Goddard Space Flight Center under the mentorship Dr. Mario Acuna (1941-2009) relating to the Juno Mission and an analysis of the Voyager 1 and 2 Missions. From 2009-2012 she worked at the University of Texas at Brownsville, at the Center for Gravitational Wave Astronomy. Where she managed and aided in the development of the only observatory in the Rio Grande Valley, the Nompuewenu Astronomical Observatory, then as assistant director of The Teacher Quality Grants Program focused in Astrobiology. After moving back to Puerto Rico, she lead the Arecibo Observatory Space Academy (2013 - 2017), a pre-college program that graduated over 300 local students from its challenging program. \r\n\r\nShe is currently a Ph.D candidate in Space Sciences at the University of Granada, working from arecibo on the study of asteroid near surfaces and their scattering properties under the mentorship of Dr Anne Virkki and Dr. Edgard Rivera-Valentin.', 'Luisa Fernanda Zambrano-Marin updates and maintains observations and data processing records in the Arecibo. She also has continuous participation in Observations Planning and Execution.', '', 'Zambrano-Marin L. F., Virkki a., Rivera-Valentin E. G., Taylor P. a. \'Scattering Laws Fit for Dual Polarization Radar Echoes of asteroids using arecibo Observatory Planetary Radar Data\' .\'  LPSC XLIX, abstract. 2018.\r\n\r\nHowell, E. S., Lejoly, C., Taylor, P. a., Rivera-Valentin, E. G., Zambrano-Marin, L. F., Giorgini, J. D., ... & Saran Bhiravarasu, S., \'arecibo radar observations of 41P/Tuttle-Giacobini-Kresák constrain the nucleus size and rotation\' . In aaS/Division for Planetary Sciences Meeting abstracts (Vol. 49). 2017.\r\n\r\nTaylor, P.a., Howell, E.S., Zambrano-Marin, L.F., Rivera-Valentin, E.G., Virkki, a., Aponte-Hernandez, B., Lopez-Oquendo, a.J., Vervack, R.J., Fernandez, Y.R., Crowell, J.L. and Margot, J.L., (2017). \'Radar and infrared observations of binary near-Earth asteroid 5143 Heracles.\'  LPSC XLVIII, abstract. 2017.\r\n\r\nTaylor, P.a., Virkki, a., Warner, B., aznar, a., Howell, E.S., Vervack, R.J., Crowell, J.L., Hinkle, M., Venditti, F., Zambrano-Marin, L.F. and Aponte-Hernandez, B., \'Radar, Optical, and Infrared Observations of Equal-Mass Binary Near-Earth asteroid (190166) 2005 uP156.\'  In aaS/Division for Planetary Sciences Meeting abstracts (Vol. 49).\r\n\r\nVirkki, a., Taylor, P. a., Zambrano-Marin, L. F., Howell, E. S., Nolan, M. C., Lejoly, C., ... & Aponte, B. a. \'Near-surface bulk densities of asteroids derived from dual-polarization radar observations\' . In European Planetary Science Congress (Vol. 11). 2017.\r\n\r\nRivera-Valentin, E.G., Taylor, P.a., Virkki, a., Saran Bhiravarasu, S., Venditti, F., Zambrano-Marin, L.F. and Aponte-Hernandez, B., \'arecibo Radar Observations of Near-Earth asteroids.\'  In AAS/Division for Planetary Sciences Meeting abstracts (Vol. 49).\r\n\r\nZambrano Marin, L. F., Nolan, M. C., Taylor, P. a., & Virkki, a.). \'Comparing near-surface and bulk densities of asteroids using radar scattering properties.\'  In aaS/Division for Planetary Sciences Meeting abstracts (Vol. 48). 2016.\r\n\r\nZambrano-Marin, L.F., Rivera-Valentin, E.G., Schmelz, J., Rodriguez-Ford, L.a., Aponte, B. and Ortiz, a.M., \'The arecibo Observatory Space academy: 4 years of STEM engagement\' . LPSC XLVII, abstract, 2617. 2016.\r\n\r\nRodriguez-Ford, L. a.; Zambrano-Marin, L. F.; Petty, B. M.; Howell, E. S.; Nolan, M. C. \'arecibo Observatory Space academy: Inspiring the next Generation of Scientists from Puerto Rico\'  46th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference, March 16-20, 2015 Woodlands, TX. LPI Contribution No. 1832, p.2783, March 2015.\r\n\r\nHowell, Ellen S.; Nolan, Michael C.; Taylor, Patrick a.; Springmann, Alessondra; Rodriguez-Ford, Linda; Zambrano-Marin, Luisa F.; Benner, Lance a.; Brozovic, Marina; Giorgini, Jon D.; Hergenrother, Carl. \'Radar images of Comet 209P/LINEAR: Constraints on shape and rotation\' American astronomical Society, DPS meeting #46, #209.24. November 2014.\r\n\r\nTaylor, Patrick a.; Warner, Brian D.; Magri, Christopher; Springmann, Alessondra; Nolan, Michael C.; Howell, Ellen S.; Miller, Kevin J.; Zambrano-Marin, Luisa F.; Richardson, James E.; Hannan, Melissa; Pravec, Petr. \'The Smallest Binary asteroid? The Discovery of Equal-Mass Binary 1994 CJ1\' American astronomical Society, DPS meeting #46, #409.03 November 2014.\r\n\r\nLuisa F Zambrano-Marin and Phil Dukes, \'World Space Week 2013: Discovering Mars, Discovering Earth\'  ad astra, the Magazine of the National Space Society, fall 2013, pg 23.\r\n\r\nLuisa Fernanda Zambrano-Marin, Dave Dressel, \'Welcome To ISDC 2013\'  ad astra, The Magazine of the National Space Society, Spring 2013; pg 11.\r\n\r\nJ. L. Elliot, M. J. Person, C. a. Zuluaga, L.F. Zambrano-Marin, et. al. \'Nature Letters: Size and albedo of Kuiper belt object 55636 from a stellar occultation\', Nature 465, 897-900 (17 June 2010) doi:10.1038/nature09109, Received 02 February 2010 & accepted 16 April 2010\r\n\r\n\'START, The use of Space Technologies\' , International Space university, Strasbourg France, 2007.\r\n\r\nFernanda Zambrano Marin, Luisa, and M. H. acuna. \'Juno Mission Fluxgate Magnetometer.\' In Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society, vol. 39, p. 977. 2', 'https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6615-4040'),
(20, NULL, NULL, 'http://www.naic.edu/ao/sites/default/files/Christiano-brum.jpg', 'Christiano Garnett Marques Brum', NULL, '242', 'Christiano.Brum@ucf.edu', NULL, 'Deputy Director of Science Operations,\r\nSAS Acting Head', 'Space & Atmospheric Sciences', 'atmosphere, galaxy', 'atmosphere', 'General Aeronomy (Troposphere), Thermosphere Coupling, Space Weather, Ionospheric Secular Changes Plasma Physics.', 'Brum\'s research includes study of long-term trends (anthropogenic or not) of the topside-protonosphere, atmospheric coupling, secular changes, medium-scale traveling ionospheric disturbances (MSTIDs), empirical and physical modeling of the ionosphere.', 'Brum graduated in Industrial Engineering from the Center for the Development of Technology and Human Resources (1996), Masters and Doctorate in Space Geophysics from the National Institute for Space Research (INPE 1999 and 2004). He earned his post-doctorates at INPE (2004-2006 2007), Utah University (2006) and Arecibo Observatory - Cornell University (2007-2011). Brum has experience in the field of Geosciences, with an emphasis on Aeronomy and Atmospheric Sciences, acting mainly on the following themes: lower ionosphere (medium and high latitudes), topside-protonosphere, neutral thermospheric winds, and numerical modeling. Currently is the Acting Head of the AO Space and Atmospheric Science department and the Deputy Director of Science Operations.', 'Francisco Cordova (PI) and Christiano G.M. Brum (Co-PI) worked on the project titled: Restoration of Scientific Capabilities at the Arecibo Observatory after the impact of Hurricane Maria, award Number:1930772 (NSF).', '<h5>(i) Master\'s Thesis</h5>\r\n\r\nWivaldo Dantas de Asevedo Junior (2009) (Masters in Space Geophysics). Dissertation Title: \'Modelo Ionosferico Regional Parametrizado\' or \'Parametrized Regional Ionospheric Model\'. (National Institute for Space Research - INPE, Brazil). Advisers: Dr. C.G.M. Brum, Dr.Jonas Rodrigues de Souza and Dr.Jose Augusto Bittencourt.\r\n\r\n<h5>\r\n(ii) Ph.D\'s Thesis</h5>\r\n\r\nCristina Yamashita (2015) (PhD in Space Geophysics). Thesis Title: \'Estudo da Variabilidade do Fluxo Solar e Seus Efeitos no Geoespaco\' or \'Long-Term Variability of F2 Layer in the South American Sector\'. (National Institute for Space Research - INPE, Brazil). Advisers: Dr. C.G.M. Brum, Dr. Dr.Ezequiel Echer and Dr. Mariza Echer.\r\n \r\nWivaldo Dantas de Asevedo Junior (2015-2020) (PhD in Space Geophysics). Thesis Title: \'Modelo Empirico Parametrizado de Ventos Neutros Termosfericos para Baixas e Medias Latitudes Baseado em Estatisticas de Dados Registrados pelo UARS-WINDII\'. (Universidade Federal do Rio Grande do Norte: Centro de Ciencias Exatas e da Terra). Advisers: Prof. Dr. Jose Henrique Fernandez (CCETU–FRN) and Dr. Christiano Garnett Marques Brum (NAIC).\r\n\r\n \r\n<h5>\r\n(iii) Postdocs</h5>\r\n\r\nDr. Rajkumar Hajra (2015). Project title: \'A long-term study on the variability of HILDCAA events and solar wind-magnetosphere coupling\'. Supervisor: Christiano Garnett Marques Brum.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h5>(iv) Scientific Initiation (Brazilian Research Experience for Undergraduates Program)</h5>\r\n\r\nMarcus Vinicius Pera de Pina (2006) [Universidade de Taubate - UNITAU]. Project Title: \'Estudo da climatologia ionosferica sobre a regiao sudeste mediante variacoes globais e locais da atividade geomagnetica\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Jose Henrique Fernandez (UNITAU).\r\n\r\nEduardo da Costa Paul (2006) [Universidade de Taubate - UNITAU]. Project Title: \'Estudo da climatologia ionosferica sobre a regiao sudeste mediante variacoes globais e locais da atividade geomagnetica\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Jose Henrique Fernandez (UNITAU).\r\n\r\n(v) Arecibo Observatory Research Experience for Undergraduates & Teachers (AO-REU & RET)\r\n\r\nSophia Salazar (2019) [New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology]. Project Title: \'First Survey of Lightning Impacts on the Lower Ionosphere Over Arecibo\'. C.G.M. Brum (AO), Pedrina Morais Terra dos Santos (AO) and Caitano L. da Silva (New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology).\r\n\r\nHillary Bermudez – Teacher (2018) [Universidad de Puerto Rico, Mayaguez]. Project Title: \'PAAPR: STEAM Curriculum\'. Mentors: Andres Diaz, Anne Virkki, Kristen Jones, Nipuni Palliyaguru, Christiano Brum, Eliana Nossa and Andrew Ortiz.\r\n\r\nJose Perez Sanabria – Teacher (2018) [CROEV, Villalba]. Project Title: \'PAPAS3 Curriculum\'. Mentors: Andres Diaz, Anne Virkki, Kristen Jones, Nipuni Palliyaguru, Christiano Brum, Eliana Nossa and Andrew Ortiz.\r\n\r\nBrandon P. Smith (2018) [Pen State University]. Project Title: \'The effect of a magnetic storm on electron density over Arecibo\'. Mentors: S. Raizada and C.G.M. Brum (AO).\r\n\r\nKhushboo Jain (2017) [University of Illinois, Urbana Champaign]. Project Title: \'Mesospheric Na variability and dependence on geomagnetic and solar activity over Arecibo\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and S. Raizada (AO).\r\n\r\nMatthew Proctor (2016) [University of Texas at Dallas (UTD)]. Project Title: \'Retrieving the real F region peak parameters from digisonde data using Incoherent Scatter Radar measurements\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Fabiano S. Rodrigues (UTD).\r\n\r\nChristopher Lee Keele (2015) [University of Texas at Dallas (UTD)]. Project Title: \'A Comprehensive Assessment of Radio Occultation Ionospheric Measurements at Mid-Latitudes\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Fabiano S. Rodrigues (UTD).\r\n\r\nMary Elizabeth Spraggs (2015) [Western Kentucky University]. Project Title: \'Latitudinal responses of F2 peak parameters to a high- intensity long-duration continuous AE activity (HILDCAA) events\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and S. Raizada (AO).\r\n\r\nMiladys Adorno Lopez (2015) [Universidad Del Turabo]. Project Title: \'Cloud coverage, visibility and precipitation survey for Puerto Rico territory\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n\r\nEfmi Franco Diaz (2014) [University of Puerto Rico at Humacao]. Project Title: \'First observations of cosmic noise absorption over Arecibo\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nCristina M. Gonzalez Rivera (2014) [University of Puerto Rico, Rio Piedras Campus]. Project Title: \'Nocturnal E-region climatology studies using Incoherent Scatter Radar observations from Arecibo Observatory\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and S. Raizada (AO).\r\n \r\nCaitlin Kerr (2013) [Massachusetts Institute of Technology - MIT]. Project Title: \'Neutral Potassium in the Thermosphere: What\'s going on?\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Jonathan Friedman (AO).\r\n \r\nTeresa Symons (2012) [Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]. Project Title: \'Solar activity effects on total electron content over Arecibo Observatory: Observational results versus IRI predictions\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nEframir Franco Diaz (2012) [Universidad de Puerto Rico, Campus Humacao]. Project Title: \'Solar and season variability of the transition height over Arecibo Observatory\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nVicki Wei Hsu. (2011) [University of Colorado]. Project Title: \'D region meteoric smoke and neutral temperature retrieval using the poker flat incoherent scatter radar\' and \'Wave signatures in the mid-latitude ionosphere during a sudden stratospheric warming of January 2010\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum, Jonathan T. Fentzke (JHUAPL) and Larisa Goncharenko (MIT).\r\n \r\nDavid Gonzalez Alcantara (2010) [University of Puerto Rico, Mayaguez Campus]. Project Title: \'Variability of the transition height over Arecibo due to Solar and Geomagnetic activities\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nAleshka Carrion Matta (2009) [University of Puerto Rico, Rio Piedras Campus]. Project Title: \'A modeling study of foF2 and hmF2 parameters measured by the Arecibo incoherent scatter radar and comparison with IRI model predictions for solar cycles 21, 22, and 23\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nDiana Prado Garzon (2008) [University of Puerto Rico, Mayaguez Campus]. Project Title: \'Study of the topside constituents\' behavior over Arecibo: Evidence for wave propagation in the topside ionosphere\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum.\r\n \r\nEthan Engle (2008) [Case Western Reserve University]. Project Title: \'Study of the ionospheric long-trend variability over Arecibo\'. Mentor: C.G.M. Brum and Eva Robles (AO).\r\n\r\n<h5>(vi) Pre-College Saturday Research Academy</h5>\r\n \r\nFelipe Perez Toledo (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Is the ionosphere over Arecibo Observatory the same for the longest registered solar minimum (end and begin of solar cycles #23 and #24)?\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\nNatalia Montero Perez (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Is the ionosphere over Arecibo Observatory the same for the longest registered solar minimum (end and begin of solar cycles #23 and #24)?\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\nIhan Acevedo (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Comparing the F-region (O+) and plasmasphere (H++He+) contributions to the VTEC (Vertical Total Electron Content) during the anomalous solar minimum\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\nJoshua Pupo (2012) [Escuela Vocacional Antonio Luchetti Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Comparing the F-region (O+) and plasmasphere (H++He+) contributions to the VTEC (Vertical Total Electron Content) during the anomalous solar minimum\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n \r\nLaura Aponte (2012) [Escuela Padre Anibal Reyes Belen de Hatillo]. Project Title: \'Geomagnetic storms prediction for the increasing portion of solar cycle #24\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n \r\nYazmin Torres (2012) [Escuela Padre Anibal Reyes Belen de Hatillo]. Project Title: \'Geomagnetic storms prediction for the increasing portion of solar cycle #24\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\nYamilette Diaz (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Morphology of the E-region over Arecibo Observatory based on ISR radar data\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n \r\nTamara Nieves (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Morphology of the E-region over Arecibo Observatory based on ISR radar data\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n \r\nLuis Raul Gomez (2012) [Escuela Superior Santiago R. Palmer]. Project Title: \'Determination of the thermospheric atomic oxygen over the Arecibo Observatory region based on Fabry-Perot Interferometer and Incoherent Scatter Radar data\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n \r\nAlexis Serrano (2012) [Escuela Superior Santiago R. Palmer]. Project Title: \'Determination of the thermospheric atomic oxygen over the Arecibo Observatory region based on Fabry-Perot Interferometer and Incoherent Scatter Radar data\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\nGabriel Amador (2012) [Colegio San Felipe de Arecibo]. Project Title: \'Determination of the thermospheric atomic oxygen over the Arecibo Observatory region based on Fabry-Perot Interferometer and Incoherent Scatter Radar data\'. Mentors: C.G.M. Brum and Edvier Cabassa.\r\n\r\n<h5>(vii) Others</h5>\r\n\r\nAndy J. Lopez Oquendo [Escuela Petra Mercado Bougart] (2015) \'Variabilidad de la protonosfera/\'topside ionosphere\' basadas en medidas indirectas de TEC y densidad de electrones\'. Mentors: C.G.M.', 'Pedrina Terra, Fabio Vargas, Christiano Brum and Ethan Miller (2020)\'Geomagnetic and Solar dependency of MSTIDs occurrence rate: A climatology based on airglow observations from the Arecibo Observatory Remote Optical Facility (ROF)\'. Journal of Geophysical Research-Space Physics, in press.\r\n\r\nFabio Vargas, Christiano Brum, Pedrina Terra & Delano Gobbi (2020). \'Mean Zonal Drift Velocities of Plasma Bubbles Estimated from Keograms of Nightglow All-Sky Images from the Brazilian Sector\'. Multidisciplinary Digital Publishing Institute (MDPI)-Atmosphere. doi: 10.3390/atmos11010069.\r\n \r\ndos Santos, Â. M., Batista, I. S., Abdu, M. A., Sobral, J. H. A., de Souza, J. R., and Brum, C. G. M. (2019) \'Climatology of intermediate descending layers (or 150?km echoes) over the equatorial and low-latitude regions of Brazil during the deep solar minimum of 2009\', Annales Geophysicae., 37, 1005–1024. doi:10.5194/angeo-37-1005-2019.\r\n \r\nP. P. Joshi, L. S. Waldrop and C. G. M. Brum (2018). \'Ionospheric O+ Momentum Balance Through Charge Exchange With Thermospheric O Atoms\'. Journal of Geophysical Research-Space Physics, 123, 9743-9761. doi:10.1029/2018JA025821.\r\n \r\nRaizada, S.; C.G.M. Brum; Mathews, J. D.; Gonzalez, C. and Franco, E. (2018). Characteristics of nighttime E-region over Arecibo: Dependence on solar flux and geomagnetic variations. Advances in Space Research, V.61, Issue 7, p.1850 – 1857. doi:10.1016/j.asr.2017.07.006.\r\n \r\nHajra, R.; Tsurutani, B. T.; C.G.M. Brum and Echer, E. (2017). High-speed solar wind stream effects on the topside ionosphere over Arecibo: A case study during solar minimum. Geophysical Research Letters. doi:10.1002/2017GL073805.\r\n \r\nRajkumar Hajra; Shyamal Kumar Chakraborty; Bruce T. Tsurutani; Ashish DasGupta; Ezequiel Echer; C.G.M. Brum; Walter D. Gonzalez and Jose Humberto Andrade Sobral (2016). An empirical model of ionospheric total electron content (TEC) near the crest of the equatorial ionization anomaly (EIA). Journal of Space Weather and Space Climate, May. doi:10.1051/swsc/2016023.\r\n\r\nS. Raizada; C.G.M. Brum; C. A. Tepley; J. S. Friedman; John. D. Mathews; F.T. Djuth and Caitlin Kerr (2015). First simultaneous measurements of Na and K thermospheric layers along with TILs from Arecibo. Geophysical Research Letters. doi:10.1002/2015GL066714.\r\n \r\nAbdu, M.A.; Brum, C.G.M.; Batista, P.P.; Gurubaran, S.; Pancheva, D.; Bageston, J. V.; Batista, I.S. and Takahashi, H. (2015). Fast and ultrafast Kelvin wave modulations of the equatorial evening F region vertical drift and spread F development. Earth, Planets and Space, 67. doi:10.1186/s40623-014-0143-5.\r\n \r\nRajkumar H