Letters, v. 33, n. L07107, p. 1-4. doi:10.1029/2005GL024837.\r\n \r\nAbdu, M.A.; Batista, I.S.; Carrasco, A.J. and Brum, C.G.M. (2005). South Atlantic magnetic anomaly ionization: A review and a new focus on electrodynamic effects in the equatorial ionosphere. Journal of Atmospheric and Solar-Terrestrial Physics, v.67, p.1643 – 1657. doi:10.1016/j.jastp.2005.01.014.\r\n \r\nContreira, D.B.; Rodrigues, F.S.; Makita, K.; Brum, C.G.M.; Gonzales, W.D.; Trived, N.B.; Silva, M.R. and Schuch, N.J. (2005). An experiment to study solar flare effects on radio-communication signals. Advances in Space Research, v. 36, n. 12, p. 2455-2459. doi:10.1016/j.asr.2004.03.019.\r\n \r\nRodrigues, F.S.; Brum, C.G.M.; Makita, K.; Nishino, M.; de Paula, E.R.; Abdu, M.A.; Nozaki, K.; Contreira, D.B.; Silva, M.R. and Schuch, N.J. (2004). A commercial radio receiver for lower ionosphere monitoring: Initial results. Geofisica Internacional, Mexico, v. 43, n. 2, p. 193-198.', 'https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6515-7621');
INSERT INTO `science_staff_3` (`ID`, `Hora_de_inicio`, `Hora_de_finalización`, `IMAGE`, `FULL_NAME`, `FIRST_NAME`, `PHONE_EXT`, `PRIMARY_EMAIL`, `UCF_EMAIL`, `POSITION`, `DEPARTMENT`, `CATEGORIES`, `KEYWORDS`, `RESEARCH_AREAS`, `RESEARCH_DESCRIPTION`, `BIOGRAPHY`, `PROJECTS`, `MENTORING`, `PUBLICATIONS`, `ORCID_LINK`) VALUES
(21, NULL, NULL, 'http://outreach.naic.edu/ao/sites/default/files/Mike-Sultzer.jpg', 'Michael Peter Sulzer', NULL, '255', 'Michael.Sulzer@ucf.edu', NULL, 'Head Of Radar Sciences, Sas', 'Space & Atmospheric Sciences', 'atmosphere, radar', 'atmosphere', 'Incoherent Scatter Radar, Ionospheric Modification, Ionospheric Physics', 'I am currently interested in investigating the physics describing the formation of various types of irregularities in the ionosphere as produced by a powerful HF wave, and deriving the spectrum of incoherent scatter plasma line from a narrow peak in the electron velocity density function.  I have worked before on other aspects of the HF modified ionosphere, the incoherent scatter spectrum in the F region when Coulomb collision are important, and various radar techniques for the Arecibo 430 MHz radar.', '\r\nMichael Peter Sulzer received his B.A. in Physics, Wesleyan University, Middletown, Connecticut in June, 1970 and his Master\'s in Electrical Engineering at Pennsylvania State University in March, 1974. Later he earned his Ph.D. in Electrical Engineering, Pennsylvania State University in January, 1979. He moved onto become a Research Associate National Astronomy and Ionosphere at Center Cornell University (February 1981 - May 1986) and Case Western Reserve University, Department of Electrical Engineering and Applied Physics January 1979 - February 1981.\r\n\r\nSince 2000, Sulzer has worked with the National Astronomy and Ionosphere at Center Cornell University and NAIC extensively. He is the Head of Radar Sciences in NAIC while being a Senior Research Associate at the National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center in Cornell University since 1986. Prior to this position, from 1991 to 2000, he was the Head of Ionospheric Modification Department in NAIC. During this time, from January 1989 to 2000, he was Senior Research Associate National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center Cornell University before working as the Acting Head of Electronics Department National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center Cornell University\r\n(September 1988 - January 1989).\r\n\r\n', 'Currents projects include finding the spectrum of the plasma line with narrow peaks in the electron velocity density function, using data from the last HF campaign to investigate the production of unusual irregularities, working on the 430 transmitter upgrade project, and planning for the new data taking system.', 'Currently mentoring a new SAS radar staff member', '<h5>Peer-reviewed first-author publications</h5> \r\nSulzer MP, Aponte N and Gonzalez SA (2005), &#34;Application of linear regularization methods to Arecibo vector velocities&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 110(A10), pp. n/a-n/a.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP (2004), &#34;Meteoroid velocity distribution derived from head echo data collected at Arecibo during regular world day observations&#34;, Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics. Vol. 4(4), pp. 947-954.\r\n\r\nSulzer M (2003), &#34;RADAR | Incoherent Scatter Radar&#34;, In Encyclopedia of Atmospheric Sciences . Oxford , pp. 1812 - 1819. Academic Press.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP and Gonzalez SA (1996), &#34;Simultaneous measurements of O+ and H+ temperatures in the topside ionosphere over Arecibo&#34;, Geophysical Research Letters. Vol. 23(22), pp. 3235-3238.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP and Fejer JA (1994), &#34;Radar spectral observations of HF-induced ionospheric Langmuir turbulence with improved range and time resolution&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 99(A8), pp. 15035-15050.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP (1993), &#34;A new type of alternating code for incoherent scatter measurements&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 28(6), pp. 995-1001.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP and Fejer JA (1991), &#34;Simultaneous observations of 46.8-MHz and 430-MHz radar backscatter from HF-induced ionospheric Langmuir turbulence&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 96(A10), pp. 17891-17895.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP (1989), &#34;Recent incoherent scatter techniques&#34;, Advances in Space Research . Vol. 9(5), pp. 153-162.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP, Ierkic HM and Fejer JA (1989), &#34;Observational limitations on the role of Langmuir cavitons in ionospheric modification experiments at Arecibo&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 94(A6), pp. 6841-6854.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP (1986), &#34;A phase modulation technique for a sevenfold statistical improvement in incoherent scatter data-taking&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 21(4), pp. 737-744.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP (1986), &#34;A radar technique for high range resolution incoherent scatter autocorrelation function measurements utilizing the full average power of klystron radars&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 21(6), pp. 1033-1040.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP and Woodman RF (1985), &#34;Pulse compression hardware decoding techniques for MST radars&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 20(6), pp. 1146-1154.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP and Woodman RF (1984), &#34;Quasi-complementary codes: A new technique for MST radar sounding&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 19(1), pp. 337-344.\r\n\r\nSulzer MP, Mathews JD and Tomko AA (1982), &#34;A UHF cross-modulation D region heating experiment with aeronomic implications&#34;, Radio Science. Vol. 17(2), pp. 435-443.\r\n  \r\n<br>\r\n<h5>Co-authored peer-reviewed publications</h5>\r\n\r\nEdlyn V. Levine,  Paul A. Bernhardt,  Michael P. Sulzer,  Peter J. Sultan, Brian S. Henderson, Eliana Nossa , Stanley C. Briczinski,  Phil Perillat,  Plasma Cavity Formation During Ionospheric Heating at Arecibo, 07 May 2020 https://doi.org/10.1029/2019JA027715\r\n\r\nRaizada S, Smith J, Lautenbach J, Aponte N, Perillat P, Sulzer M and Mathews J (2020), &#34;New Lidar Observations of Ca+ in the Mesosphere and Lower Thermosphere Over Arecibo&#34;, Geophysical Research Letters. Vol. 47(5), pp. e2020GL087113.\r\n\r\nMahmoudian A, Nossa E, Isham B, Bernhardt P, Briczinski S and Sulzer M (2019), &#34;Narrowband Stimulated Electromagnetic Emission (NSEE) Yielding Electron Temperature Measurements at the Arecibo Observatory&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 0(ja)\r\n\r\nGong Y, Ma Z, Lv X, Zhang S, Zhou Q, Aponte N and Sulzer M (2018), &#34;A Study on the Quarterdiurnal Tide in the Thermosphere at Arecibo During the February 2016 Sudden Stratospheric Warming Event&#34;, Geophysical Research Letters. Vol. 45(23), pp. 13,142-13,149.\r\n\r\nRout D, Chakrabarty D, Sarkhel S, Sekar R, Fejer BG, Reeves GD, Kulkarni AS, Aponte N, Sulzer M, Mathews JD, Kerr RB and Noto J (2018), &#34;The Ionospheric Impact of an ICME-Driven Sheath Region Over Indian and American Sectors in the Absence of a Typical Geomagnetic Storm&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. Vol. 123(5), pp. 4298-4308.\r\n\r\nVierinen J, Gustavsson B, Hysell DL, Sulzer MP, Perillat P and Kudeki E (2017), &#34;Radar Observations of Thermal Plasma Oscillations in the Ionosphere&#34;, Geophysical Research Letters. , pp. n/a-n/a.\r\n  \r\nPradipta R, Lee M-C, Coster AJ, Tepley CA, Sulzer MP and Gonzalez SA (2017), &#34;Ionospheric plasma disturbances generated by naturally occurring large-scale anomalous heat sources&#34;, Journal of Atmospheric and Solar-Terrestrial Physics . Vol. 156, pp. 15 - 23.\r\n\r\nHysell DL, Vierinen J and Sulzer MP (2017), &#34;On the theory of the incoherent scatter gyrolines&#34;, Radio Science. , pp. n/a-n/a.\r\n\r\nZhang S-R, Erickson PJ, Zhang Y, Wang W, Huang C, Coster AJ, Holt JM, Foster JF, Sulzer M and Kerr R (2017), &#34;Observations of ion-neutral coupling associated with strong electrodynamic disturbances during the 2015 St. Patrick&#71;s Day storm&#34;, Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics. , pp. n/a-n/a. John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.\r\n\r\nHysell DL, Larsen M and Sulzer M (2016), &#34;Observational evidence for new instabilities in the midlatitude E and F region&#34;, Annales Geophysicae. Vol. 34(11), pp. 927-941.\r\n\r\nGong Y, Zhou Q, Zhang S, Aponte N and Sulzer M (2016), &#34;An incoherent scatter radar study of the midnight temperature maximum